{
  "texts": [
    "Finally, it elaborates on the integration of this layer into the generic Mistral LLM framework.",
    "Probabilistic Inference TheoryIn the advanced theoretical framework of probabilistic inference for LLMs, we employ sophisticated mathematical constructs, including matrix calculus and equations reminiscent of complex physics principles like Bernoulli's and Lorentz transformations.",
    "These constructs enable a deeper and more dynamic analysis of probabilistic relationships in language models.The fundamental Bayesian equation is extended with matrix calculus to accommodate the multi-dimensional nature of data in LLMs: P(H|E) = P(E|H) • P(H) P(E) In this matrix form, P(H|E) is the posterior probability matrix of hypotheses H given evidence E, P(E|H) is the likelihood matrix, P(H) represents the prior probability matrix of hypotheses, and P(E) is the evidence probability matrix.To further enhance the probabilistic model, we integrate principles analogous to Bernoulli's principle and Lorentz transformations, which are used to model the dynamics of fluid flow and relativistic effects, respectively.",
    "In our context, these principles are adapted to describe the fluidity and relativistic effects in the evolving probabilities within an LLM's inference process:P ′ = 1 1 -v 2 c 2 - ∂P ∂t + u • ∇P + P • ∇ • u - v • P c 2 v (1)Here, ∆P represents the change in the probability matrix, reflecting the dynamic and fluid nature of probabilistic reasoning in LLMs.",
    "The term u signifies the 'velocity' of change in the context or input data, and c is a constant analogous to the speed of light, representing the maximum rate of information processing in the model."
  ]
}